.TH "drm_property_create_bitmask" 9 "drm_property_create_bitmask" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
drm_property_create_bitmask \- create a new bitmask property type
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "struct drm_property *" drm_property_create_bitmask
.BI "(struct drm_device *dev "  ","
.BI "u32 flags "  ","
.BI "const char *name "  ","
.BI "const struct drm_prop_enum_list *props "  ","
.BI "int num_props "  ","
.BI "uint64_t supported_bits "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "dev" 12
drm device
.IP "flags" 12
flags specifying the property type
.IP "name" 12
name of the property
.IP "props" 12
enumeration lists with property bitflags
.IP "num_props" 12
size of the \fIprops\fP array
.IP "supported_bits" 12
bitmask of all supported enumeration values
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This creates a new bitmask drm property which can then be attached to a drm
object with \fBdrm_object_attach_property\fP. The returned property object must
be freed with \fBdrm_property_destroy\fP, which is done automatically when
calling \fBdrm_mode_config_cleanup\fP.

Compared to plain enumeration properties userspace is allowed to set any
or'ed together combination of the predefined property bitflag values
.SH "RETURN"
A pointer to the newly created property on success, NULL on failure.
